{"/service/ndnp/dlc/batch_dlc_beiderbecke_ver01/data/sn83045462/00280657414/1923110401/0424.xml":{"full_text":"38\nMARKET REVERSAL\nRARO TO EXPLAIN\nFundamental Conditions Had\nNot Changed When Steel\n\u201cExtra\u201d Was Voted.\nGARY\u2019S VIEWS HELPED\nConfidence in Business Outlook Ap\npears Improved\u2014Bonds\nTurn Stronger.\nUV GEORGE T. HUGHES.\nSpecial Dispatch to The Star.\nXEW YORK, November 3.\u2014Without\ntioubt the most spectacular evept of\nthe week in the security markets was\nthe declaration of an extra dividend\nof 14 of 1 per cent on the common\nf-tock of tho United Suites Steel Cor\n2'oration, together with the publica\ntion of an earnings statement far\nmore favorable than Wall street had\nanticipated.\nMore important than the action it\nself was the inference from the ac\ntion that the steel directors had con\nfidence in tho business outlook. Judge\nGary\u2019s statement on this point was\n'he most reassuring heard in weeks.\nThe result was a violent advance in\nstock of nearly all grades, but es\npecially those in which the largo\n\u25a0\u2019short\" interest existed. The retreat\nof this short interest was helped\nalong by the optimistic statement of\n1 professional speculator whoso career\nhas been the subject of a great deal\nof attention, and who completely re\nversed the position he took six months\nago.\nRise Not Doe to Ckangn.\nThis turnabout in speculative sen\ntiment came without any change in\nthe fundamentals of the business sit\nuation. There remained much as\nthey had been for the past month\nor so. Money continued easy and\n\u2022Tedit abundant. Railroad car load\nings Were at almost their record\nhigh. Chain stores and mail order\nhouses still were reporting very\nlarge sales. The outlook for the au\ntomobile Industry could not be clear\nly discerned until the seasonal lull\nnow prevailing is over and some line\ncould be secured on the spring de\nmand. The oil trade was still strug\ngling with excessive production and\nthe rubber and tire manufacturers\nwith intense competition.\nCotton quotations soared to new\nhighs, while the textile manufactur\ners were In grave doubt as to just\nhow much of the additional cost of\nthe raw material they could pass\non to the ultimate consumer. Per\nhaps the most favorable feature was\nthe belter situation of the farmer\nexcept possibly the wheat producer,\nnnd even his position was certainly\nno worse.\nMove Called Psychological.\nIt can be fairly said then that the\napparent reversal of opinion was psy\nchological. Evidently the profession\nsi! traders In securities, whose gloomy\noutgivings had saturated the Wall\nstreet atmosphere for the past three\n\u25a0months, were no longer able to com\nmand so attentive an audience. The\nchange is important in two ways.\nFor one thing, the business man is\nrelieved, for the moment at least, of\nthe doubt as to the business future\nwhich the spectacle of steadily fall\ning prices always raises in his mind.\nIn the second place, it clears the way\nfor the stock market to resume its\nmajor function of forecasting trade\ndevelopment. Whether the improve\nment In prices will go further or\n\u2022will be even maintained at its pres\nent level no one can say, but the\nverdict of the market will be looked\nto with more respect than was ac\ncorded the fluctuations of the pre\nceding weeks, dominated as they\n\u2022cere by purely professional specu\nlators.\nVital Bearing on Stocks.\nComing hack to the action of the\ndirectors of the Steel Corporation as\nto the dividend on the common stock,\nit has an important bearing upon\nthe investment status of the stocks*\nof all the stronger industrials and\nutilities. When the American Tele\nphone and Telegraph Company placed\nits stock on a 9 per cent basis and\nstarted its campaign for a wider dis\ntribution of Us shares many doubts\nwere expressed as to the wisdom of\n\u2019ho move. The result, however, has\nbeen to give this great utility the\nlargest number of stockholders of\nany American corporation, has stab\nilized the market for its securities\nand contributed largely toward abet\nter understanding with the public.\nThe steel directors probably have no\nintention of going so far. but noth\ning could he more encouraging to\n\u2022he small shareholder than putting\n.steel common permanently on a 6\nper cent basis, toward which the ex\ntra seems to point,\nAdrqmtr Return* Neceeeery.\nIn thes\u00a7 days of high income sur\ntaxes the man of large wealth can\nno longer be relied upon to hold eom\n\u2022non\u2019stock. half the dividend on which\nhe must pay back to the government.\nSome one must take his place, and if\nthis Is to be the small investor he\nmust have a more adequate return\n\u25a0\u00bbhan It has been the practice of the\n-Steel Corporation to give. There are\n.1 few other largo corporations, in\ncluding probably at least one rail\nroad\u2014the Atchison \u2014which could\n\u2022\u2022also tholr dividend rates without\ntransgressing the limits of conser\nvatism If financing is to be done by\n\u2022Bsue of stocks instead of constantly\nincreasing bonded Indebtedness the\nrailroads will have to come to this.\nAlways excepting the foreign ex\nchanges, the markets continue to\nignore the outlook abroad. Exchange\nrates fluctuate rapidly, but foreign\nbonds remain quiet and steady. More\nInterest is taken in securi\nties than in the foreign.\nBonds Appear Stronger.\nIn the bond market there has been a\nremarkable display of underlying\nstrength In all high-grade obliga-!\nrlons. Investment bankers are much\nencouraged at the outlook. There Is\nno sign of any rise in money rates;\nin fact, the tendency seems to be the\nother way. That being the case, there\nhas been a turning of attention to\nlong-term, low-coupon rate bonds,\nwhich has been reflected In the quo\ntation for that class of security. Most\nseasoned issues of this grade are still\nselling under the high points of the\nyear, so there is room for improve\nment, regardless of the comparatively\nsmall yield the best of thssu bonds\ngive at present prices.\nCopyright. 1828.\nDROP IN SUGAR HALTS.\n\nBaw Futures Go Higher on Cov\nering by Trade.\nNEW YORK, November 3.\u2014The raw\nsugar market was steady today, but\nno sales were reported and prices\nwere unchanged, with Cubaa quoted\nat 6%, cost and freight, equal to 6.91\nfor centrifugal.\nRaw sugar futures were steadier\nand prices were higher on covering\nand trade buying, prompted by re\nports of a better Inquiry for refined.\nFinal prices were at about the best\nand S to 11 points net higher. De\ncember closed at 5.00; March, 3.96;\nMay. 4.08; July, 4.11.\nThere were no changes In refined\nsugar prices, which are listed at from\n8.40 to 8.70 for fine granulated, but\na better inquiry was reported.\nCHICAGO MARKET.\nCHICAGO. November 3.\u2014 Libby, Mc-\nNeill. 6%; Swift A Co.. 101 ft: Swift\nInternational, 17%; Union Carbide,\n\u00a34%; Wrtgley,* 118; Yellow Manufac\nturing \u201cB,\" 36%; Yellow Taxi, 118.\nFINANCIAL,\nNEW YORK STOCK EXCHANGE\nWEEK ENDED NOVEMBER 3, 1923\nI\u2014lM1 \u20141M8\u2014s Dlt. Week ending Veveaber 8, 1018. Met,\nL \u00b0w- High. lew. Rate. High. lew. Oleee. Chge.\nJ, 48 82 67 5 Adams Express 68 67 68 \u20141\n23 10% I9bj G\\ii Advance Uumley 7 6% 7\n66 45% 72% 56 4 Air Reduction 64% 62% 6416 +l%\n18% 9% 14% 4% Ajax Rubber 6 6% 6\n91% 55% 80 59% 4 Allied Chemical A Dye.... 64% 60% 64% +2%\n59% 87% 61% 37% 4 Allls-Chalmers Mfg 41% 88 41% +B%\n\u00a32% 27% 86% 10% Am Agriculture Chemical. 11% 10% 10% ft%\n72% 55% 68% 28% Am Agriculture Chem pf.. 31% 28% 81+44\n49 31% 49% 25 American Beet Sugar 88% SO 88%\n49 31% 60 American Bosch Magneto. 27 22% 27% +4%\n88% 51 83% 69% 5 Am Brake S Foundry... 72% 70% 72 +1\n<6% 82% 106 73% 5 American Can 99% 190% 99% +B%\n113% 93% 115 106 7 AmerlcanCan pf 107 l(fe% 107\n201 141 189 148% 12 American Car Foundry. 160% 165 160% +5%\n26% 20% 2 Am Chain class Aw 1 21% 21% 21%\nJ* 0 15% 5% American Chicle 15% 11% 16% +